                "attribute": "unordered",
                "list_items": [
                    {
                        "item_type": "text",
                        "item_content": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "content": "reasonably likely to identify the source of a wire or electronic communication.\"18 U.S.C."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "item_type": "text",
                        "item_content": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "content": "δ 3127(4)."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                122,
                91,
                818,
                146
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "4. In the context of traditional phone communications, pen registers capture the destination phone numbers of outgoing calls and texts sent from a phone, while trap and trace devices capture the phone numbers of incoming calls and texts received by a phone. Similar principles apply to other kinds of wire and electronic communications, including Intermet communications, which most phones today are used to send and receive in addition to phone communications."
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                120,
                158,
                839,
                344
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "5. On the Internet, data transferred between devices is not sent as a continuous stream, but rather the data are split into discrete \"packets.\" Generally, a single communication is sent as a series of packets. When the packets reach their destination, the receiving device reassembles them into the complete communication. Each packet has two parts: a \"header,\" which contains routing and control information, and a \"payload,\" which generally contains user data."
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                120,
                356,
                864,
                541
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "6. In particular, a packet header reflects the following information:"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                178,
                554,
                730,
                574
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "• the source IP address' from which the packet was sent and the destination IP address to which the packet is directed;"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                235,
                587,
                854,
                640
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "• the communications port associated with the packet, reflecting the type of communication involved (e.g., web, email, FTP); and"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                235,
                655,
                833,
                708
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "• the date/time of the communication."
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                236,
                723,
                545,
                740
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "page_footnote",
            "content": {
                "page_footnote_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "1 Every device on the Internet is identified by a unique number called an Internet protocol (\"IP\") address. This number is used to route information between devices, for example, between two computers."
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                120,
                817,
                861,
                870
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "page_footer",
            "content": {
                "page_footer_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "2017.02.06"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                122,
                901,
                181,
                914
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "page_number",
            "content": {
                "page_number_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "2"
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                488,
                886,
